âteau-Auffrique, Aisne, Picardie, France":"Coucy-le-Château-Auffrique, Aisne, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"DE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"COUCY","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Cornwall and Devon): nickname from Middle English <i>couch(e)</i> ‘hump, hunch’, used for a hunchback. In Cornwall and Devon it is usually pronounced as <i>Cooch</i>.","English (Cornwall and Devon): variant of   Gooch  .","English (Cornwall and Devon): from Middle English <i>coche</i>, <i>couche</i> ‘bed, couch, tablecloth’ (Old French <i>couche</i>, <i>culche</i>). It could have been a metonymic occupational name for someone who made such items or a nickname for a lazy individual. Alternatively, it could have been applied to someone who produced <i>couchwork</i>, a luxurious embroidery in which gold or silver thread and jewels were sewn into satin or silk robes."],"variants":[{"name":"Gooch","meanings":["English (East Anglia): from the rare Middle English personal name <i>Goche</i> (also found as <i>Joche</i>). It was current in East Anglia from the early 12th to the early 13th centuries as a variant of Anglo-Norman French <i>Go(s)ce</i>, <i>Jo(s)ce</i>, a pet form of Old French <i>Goscelin</i>.","English: alternatively, a nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>gouge</i> (from Latin <i>gobio</i>), the nominative form of Old French <i>goujon</i> (from Latin <i>gobionem</i>) ‘gudgeon’, perhaps for a gullible person.","Welsh: in southwestern England, possibly an Anglicized form of Welsh <i>coch</i>, <i>goch</i> ‘red(-haired)’, though the sound change is irregular. Compare   Gough  . It may also be a variant of Cornish and Welsh   Couch  , with the same meaning."]},{"name":"Gush","meanings":["English (Devon and Dorset): probably a variant of <b>Gudge</b>, itself a variant of   Couch   or   Gooch  ."]},{"name":"Coach","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Couch  .","Possibly also an Americanized form of French Canadian or French   Coache  ."]}]},{"name":"Guy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of a compound name starting with <i>witu</i> ‘wood’ or <i>wīt</i> ‘wide’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England. In Old French initial <i>w-</i> regularly became <i>gu-</i>. The usual Norman forms of the name were <i>Gy</i> or <i>Guido</i>. In medieval Latin the same name is found as <i>Wido</i>. It was a popular name among the Normans, enhanced no doubt by the romance of Guy of Warwick, recounting the exploits of a folk hero of the Crusades."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guy DE COUCY was born about 1110, in Thourotte, Oise, Hauts-de-France, France, his father, Guy De Coucy II, was 18 and his mother, Richilde de la Fere, was 19. He married Jeanne de Thourotte in 1134. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died in 1170, in his hometown, at the age of 61."},"et":{"ABT 1110–1170":"umbes 1110–1170","1110–1170":"1110–1170","1119–1163":"1119–1163","1135–1177":"1135–1177","1144–1192":"1144–1192","1152–1214":"1152–1214","1093–1140":"1093–1140","1092–1146":"1092–1146","1110":"1110","1152":"1152","1163":"1163","114